ons with friends and neighbors, and local and provincial-level leaders—as occupier and occupied—are documented. Their stories climax during the two-month period in early 1776 when Goforth was military governor of Three Rivers and Badeaux served as his somewhat reluctant interpreter and unofficial advisor. Including their experiences with Benedict Arnold and Quebec's Governor Guy Carleton, as well as letters to Benjamin Franklin and John Jay, this unique book provides diverse insights into the invasion of Canada and its immediate impact on the people on both sides of the revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCanadian Invasion, 1775-1776vSources. 0aCanadian Invasion, 1775-1776. 4aHistory : American History. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Military.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Mark R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeadows, Teresa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846005540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438460055423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438460055/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles